Mobile performance rules ([README_04](docs/README_04_DEVELOPMENT_PRODUCTION_ROADMAP.md) §7):

- Target stable 60 FPS on mid-range mobile devices when possible; 30 FPS fallback acceptable.
- Large maps: layered TileMaps and staged sectors — not single huge bitmaps.
- Use the Mobile renderer and project settings tuned for handheld (see `project.godot`).
- Pool enemies, projectiles, VFX, damage numbers, and UI popups — avoid `queue_free()` churn during active waves.
- Avoid per-frame array/dictionary churn and unnecessary `.duplicate()` in gameplay loops.
- Avoid instancing/freeing nodes during active waves except during early prototype.
- Avoid `get_node()` / `get_child()` calls in combat loops; cache references in `_ready()`.
- Keep texture atlases organized by feature: heroes, enemies, towers, UI, VFX.
- Keep VFX readable and limited; do not flood the screen.
- Use `Area2D`, simple colliders, or manual squared-distance range checks; avoid heavy physics simulation.
- Prefer squared distance checks when comparing ranges.
- Avoid rebuilding large Control trees every frame; split static and dynamic UI layers.
- Use compressed textures suitable for mobile after prototype (VRAM compression, sensible max sizes).
- Prefer `MultiMeshInstance2D` or batching-friendly setups for large enemy counts when profiling shows need.
